a&gt;&lt;&lt; &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;You assumed that Paramahamsa=\r\n, Siddha, Natha (Mahasiddha) and Rishi are fixed categories and exponential=\r\nly &quot;greater&quot; than each other.&gt;&gt; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dlef=\r\nt&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;&lt;/FON=\r\nT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVer=\r\ndana&gt;I assume because Vimalananda mentions that they are greater to each ot=\r\nher. And it sounds quite logical to me. The exponential as I told you, was =\r\nan approximation and nothing more, since you kept pestering for a &#39;formula&#39;=\r\n. BTW, Vimalananda even goes to extent of mentioning a Nath may takes thous=\r\nands of years of sadhana to pulled into a Muni and similarly a Muni may tak=\r\ne &quot;billions&quot; of years of sadhana to become a Rishi, IF, a higher being deci=\r\ndes to pull them forward. Else they can keep staying in their ever &#39;orbits&#39;=\r\n around the center, very close, yet not merging. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=\r\n=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;FONT size=3D2=\r\n&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=\r\n=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;&lt; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 s=\r\nize=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;Now, Ramakrishna himself said that Vivekananda and s=\r\nix other sishyas were &quot;Ishwara Koti&quot; or &quot;Nitya Siddhas&quot;. Can you tell me wh=\r\nere this falls on Vimalananda&#39;s scale? What do you think &quot;Nithya Siddha&quot; (n=\r\nithya=3Deternal) means? Is it Siddha or Mahasiddha or even greater or in be=\r\ntween? If six disciples were &quot;Nithya Siddhas&quot; and Ramakrishna is &quot;greater&quot; =\r\nas you say, can he be a &quot;Paramahamsa&quot; on this scale, i.e. lower than them?&=\r\ngt;&gt; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=\r\n=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 siz=\r\ne=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;Simple! Ramakrishna says Vivekananda was a part of a R=\r\nishi who came down. An amsa is not a Rishi in fullforce, but sufficient par=\r\nt of the Rishi&#39;s consciousness that comes down for a secific purpose and on=\r\nce the purpose is served, goes back to the source. Similar for the 6 Nitya-=\r\nSiddhas. Therefore, very technically, Swami Vivekananda is an *amsa* of a R=\r\nishi, a projection of a Rishi. Not the Rishi is full. BTW, all of these Sid=\r\ndhas, Naths, Munis etc are projection Rishis one way or the other. Each is =\r\nkept is ingorance of their real being (Rishi) such that the play can go on =\r\n(not my words, Vimalananda&#39;s words). They are Nitya-siddha because even if =\r\nthey take birth over and over, being parts of extremely higher beings, thes=\r\ne emanations/projections/amsas will surely eventually go back to the source=\r\n when the work is done. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#0000=\r\n00 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT col=\r\nor=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;However, in their forms as specific in=\r\ndividuals like Vivekananda, whether these amsa attain the specific stages w=\r\nhich makes a siddha/nath/muni/rishi will determine if they are to be called=\r\n so. They may not need to do so since they are here for a purpose. But, the=\r\n only way a person can be called a siddha in true sense is when he, as Vima=\r\nlananda puts it, &quot;picks a petal&quot;, (some specific shaktis) an &quot;orbit&quot; and mo=\r\nves closer to the Centre and yet not merging into it, deeper and deeper.&nb=\r\nsp; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DV=\r\nerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D=\r\n2 face=3DVerdana&gt;There is a book of conversations between Totapuri and a ce=\r\nrtain sadhaka (his disciple) when Totapuri lived in Puri. He used to stay i=\r\nn the Swargadwara smashana and later someone build a small ashram for him. =\r\nTotapuri&#39;s ashram still exists in Puri. In that conversation, Totapuri also=\r\n mentions a similar ideas of what is a siddha and higher. And how only a Si=\r\nddha and none less is a true Vigyani. He further mentions that Swami Viveka=\r\nnanda did not (need) to go to the stage of a Siddha. His work was specific,=\r\n he did the work and went off. He did not need to and therefore did not bec=\r\nome a Siddha. I see zero confusion here. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;F=\r\nONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=\r\n=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;Added to this the fac=\r\nt that Vivekananda was very clear, just as all the disciples of Ramakrshna =\r\nwere clear, that Ramakrishna was a special spiritual being, and higher than=\r\n them. Here too I see no confusion. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT c=\r\nolor=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;=\r\n&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;=\r\n&lt;It is not necessary that there is a clear order of greatness. Infinity =\r\nis neither greater than nor less than nor equal to infinity.&gt;. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/=\r\nDIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp;=\r\n &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#00000=\r\n0 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;This is what I call approximation. For an ordinar=\r\ny man, all saints maybe equally elevated. For Yogis, there maybe subtle dif=\r\nferences and depths. The truth lies in the nuances. Anyway, Vivekananda&#39;s o=\r\nwn words are more reliable for me than yours on this matter. And my previou=\r\ns explanation actually clarifies this statement of Sri Ramakrishna that Viv=\r\nekananda was the &quot;ancient Rishis Nara&quot; who came down for the good of mankin=\r\nd. &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVe=\r\nrdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT co=\r\nlor=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;&lt;Wise men tread cautiously and=\r\n do not rush to judgment on others.&gt;&gt; &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft=\r\n&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;&lt;/FONT=\r\n&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerd=\r\nana&gt;I am merely quoting and putting together the analysis, statements of sp=\r\niritually great people. It is not as complex as you think! Saying that A is=\r\n fatter than B, based one statements and quotes from people who maybe in th=\r\ne know of things, is hardly a judgement. It could very well be a fact. &lt;/FO=\r\nNT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&=\r\nnbsp; &lt;FONT size=3D2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#=\r\n000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;-Regards &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FO=\r\nNT color=3D#000000 size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp;Rajarshi &lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DI=\r\nV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#000000 size=3D3 face=3DVerdana&gt;&nbsp; &lt;FONT s=\r\nize=3D2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&lt;FONT color=3D#a2a2a2 size=\r\n=3D3 face=3D&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;I&gt;Bazeecha-e-atfal hai